        "This 22-year-old female was hospitalized for right thigh pain and significant leukocytosis (initial WBC 139.3 K/uL), which led to a primary diagnosis of Chronic Myeloid Leukemia (CML). The diagnosis was definitively confirmed via cytogenetics showing a 46,XX,t(9;22)(q34;q11.2) translocation (Philadelphia chromosome) in all examined cells and a peripheral blood FISH analysis indicating 95% BCR/ABL1 positivity. Key imaging results included a spleen ultrasound showing 14.5 cm splenomegaly and a right thigh MRI demonstrating a 17 cm segment of abnormal bone marrow edema and enhancement in the distal femur, consistent with CML marrow infiltration without cortical destruction. Secondary diagnoses included anxiety, nausea, and right femur bone pain. During the hospital course, the patient was treated with hydroxyurea, fluids, and allopurinol for tumor lysis syndrome prophylaxis, and was initiated on dasatinib 100mg daily. Her pain management was transitioned from opioids to Tylenol and lidocaine patches. Due to the high risk of clots associated with her malignancy and obesity, her contraception was changed from Loestrin (estrogen-based) to norethindrone (progesterone-only). She was discharged in stable condition with a WBC count of 90.5 K/uL, with plans for indefinite dasatinib therapy and outpatient follow-ups with Hematology/Oncology and Psychiatry.": "95% Bootstrap Confidence Interval: (0.0%, 0.0%), Median: 0.0%"
