        "[Diagnosis]\nChronic Myeloid Leukemia (CML), BCR-ABL1 (Philadelphia chromosome) positive.\n\n[Lab Trends]\n- Admission: WBC 139.3 K/uL, Blasts 2%, Promyelocytes 1%, Myelocytes 4%, Metamyelocytes 12%, Bands 21%, Neutrophils 50%.\n- Discharge: WBC 90.5 K/uL, Blasts 1%, Promyelocytes 1%, Myelocytes 7%, Metamyelocytes 2%, Bands 14%, Neutrophils 66%.\n\n[Genetic Confirmation]\n- Karyotype: 46,XX,t(9;22)(q34;q11.2)[20] (Philadelphia chromosome positive in 20/20 cells).\n- FISH Analysis: 95% (190/200 cells) positive for BCR/ABL1 gene rearrangement.\n\n[Imaging Findings]\n- Spleen Ultrasound: 14.5 cm splenomegaly without focal lesions.\n- MRI Right Thigh: 17 cm length of abnormal bone marrow edema and infiltration within the distal right femur; 1 cm thick circumferential periosteal soft tissue enhancement consistent with CML-related marrow infiltration.\n\nComprehensive Discharge Summary:\nMs. ___ is a 22-year-old female admitted for evaluation of severe right thigh pain and significant leukocytosis (WBC 139.3 K/uL). Diagnostic workup, including bone marrow biopsy, cytogenetics, and FISH, confirmed a diagnosis of Philadelphia chromosome-positive Chronic Myeloid Leukemia (CML). MRI of the right thigh identified 17 cm of leukemic marrow infiltration, which was determined to be the primary cause of her bone pain. During her hospitalization, she was initially treated with Hydroxyurea (later stopped) and Allopurinol for cytoreduction and tumor lysis syndrome prophylaxis. She was successfully transitioned to targeted therapy with the tyrosine kinase inhibitor (TKI) Dasatinib 100mg daily. Pain management was optimized by transitioning from opioids to a regimen of Tylenol, lidocaine patches, and gabapentin, with orthopedic clearance for full weight-bearing. Due to the increased risk of thromboembolism associated with CML, her contraception was switched from Loestrin to progesterone-only Norethindrone. She also received psychiatric evaluation for anxiety regarding her new diagnosis. She was discharged in stable condition with instructions to continue Dasatinib indefinitely, complete 14 days of Allopurinol, and follow up closely with Hematology/Oncology and Psychiatry. She must avoid antacids (e.g., Omeprazole) as they interfere with Dasatinib absorption.": "95% Bootstrap Confidence Interval: (0.0%, 0.0%), Median: 0.0%"
